context: Nasser remains an iconic figure in the Arab world, particularly for his strides towards social justice and Arab unity, modernization policies, and <a2_0>anti-imperialist<a2_0/> efforts. His presidency also encouraged and coincided with an Egyptian cultural boom, and launched large industrial projects, including the <a0_0>Aswan Dam and Helwan City<a0_0/>. Nasser's detractors criticize his authoritarianism, his government's <a3_0>human rights violations<a3_0/>, his populist relationship with the citizenry, and his failure to establish civil institutions, blaming his legacy for future dictatorial governance in Egypt. Historians describe Nasser as a towering political figure of the Middle East in the <a1_0>20th<a1_0/> century.
